<h1>Software Design and Engineering Artifact</h1>

<h2>Artifact Description</h2>
<p>This artifact is the Grazioso Salvare Dashboard, a client/server web application developed in CS-340: Client/Server Development. The application analyzes and visualizes data from the Austin Animal Center Outcomes dataset to support animal rescue operations and assist stakeholders in making informed decisions about identifying dogs suitable for search-and-rescue training. Users can filter and analyze data based on attributes such as breed, age, and outcome type. The system was developed using Python, Dash, and Plotly for the frontend and visualization layers, while MongoDB served as the backend database. Additional tools such as Pandas were used for data manipulation, and PyMongo enabled integration between the application and the database.</p>

<h2>Enhancements Implemented</h2>
<p>The original application provided core functionality for filtering and visualizing data; however, improvements were needed to enhance maintainability, scalability, reliability, and usability for end users. To address these needs, I refactored large functions into modular components to improve code organization and maintainability and created a dedicated AnimalShelter.py class to centralize and manage database CRUD operations.
I also added structured logging and improved error handling to support debugging and system monitoring. Input validation was implemented to ensure data integrity and prevent invalid or incomplete data from being processed. In addition, database interaction efficiency was enhanced by restructuring queries for improved performance, and filtered query methods were developed to support dynamic user input and enable real-time data retrieval.
Further improvements included enhancing dynamic visualizations so that charts and maps update in real time based on user filters, as well as adding inline documentation and comments to improve readability and support future development.
